<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="intro-grid">
      <div class="intro-body">
        <p class="section-label">01 — About This Service</p>
        <h2 class="section-title">The refrigerator call is the one you don't want to ignore.</h2>
        <p>Refrigerators are the one appliance that doesn't get a day off. When something goes wrong — the fridge runs but won't cool, the ice maker stops, water pools on the floor — food is at risk within hours. That's the reality of this repair across SoCal, where the ambient heat doesn't help.</p>
        <p>Our technicians run refrigerator calls across Southern California daily. From a West Hollywood high-rise to a Newport Beach estate with a built-in Sub-Zero in the butler's pantry, from a Thousand Oaks family kitchen with a French-door Samsung to a Riverside rental with a basic top-freezer — we've seen the full range. Most refrigerators have the same failure modes regardless of price point: evaporator fan motors, condenser coils clogged with SoCal dust, defrost system failures, compressor issues. Our guys know exactly what they're walking into.</p>
        <p>We carry parts for the brands we see most often. That means the majority of refrigerator repairs get done on the first visit — not "we'll need to order that part and come back Thursday."</p>

        <div class="tip-box">
          <div class="tip-label">🌡 Southern California Climate Note</div>
          <p>SoCal's warm, dry climate — coastal humidity at the beaches, dry heat in the valleys, dust in the high desert — means refrigerator condenser coils accumulate dust and pet hair faster than in cooler regions. A fridge that was cooling fine last winter might struggle this summer not because anything broke, but because the coils are overdue for cleaning. We include a coil inspection with every refrigerator service call.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="diy-box">
          <div class="diy-label">🔧 Before You Call — 4 Quick Checks</div>
          <h3>Try these in 10 minutes — they fix maybe 25% of "not cooling" calls before we even dispatch.</h3>
          <ol>
            <li><strong>Clean the condenser coils.</strong> Pull the fridge out, vacuum the coils on the back or bottom (depending on model). If you can write your name in the dust, this is your problem.</li>
            <li><strong>Check the door gasket seal.</strong> Close the door on a dollar bill — if it slides out without resistance, the gasket is leaking and the compressor is overworking.</li>
            <li><strong>Verify the thermostat setting.</strong> Sounds obvious — but kids, cleaning, and curious cats bump dials. Fridge should be 37–40°F, freezer 0°F.</li>
            <li><strong>Check power and the breaker.</strong> Listen for the compressor hum. If silent, check the outlet with another appliance and confirm the breaker isn't tripped.</li>
          </ol>
        </div>
      </div>

