<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">07 — Repair or Replace?</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">When does it make sense to fix it vs buy new?</h2>
    <p class="lead">We tell you straight which side of the line your unit falls on — even when "replace" is the answer. Here's the rubric our technicians actually use on a service call.</p>

    <div class="rvr-grid">
      <div class="rvr-card">
        <span class="rvr-verdict repair">Almost always repair</span>
        <h3>Sub-Zero · Thermador · Viking · Wolf · Miele</h3>
        <p>Built for 20+ year service lives. Replacement runs $5,000 to $15,000+ before installation, panel-matching, and disposal. Even a $1,500 compressor replacement on a Sub-Zero is pennies on the dollar versus a new unit. Parts continue to be supported by the manufacturer for 15-20 years after model end-of-life.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Sealed-system repair worth it through year 18-20</li>
          <li>Cosmetic and gasket repairs always worth it</li>
          <li>Control board replacement: yes, even at $700-$1,200</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="rvr-card">
        <span class="rvr-verdict judge">Judgment call — use the rule</span>
        <h3>Samsung · LG · Whirlpool · KitchenAid · GE · Frigidaire</h3>
        <p>Mid-market units have an honest 10-year design life. Past that, parts are still available but the rest of the unit is aging in parallel — fix the compressor and the icemaker fails 8 months later.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Under 10 years old AND repair under $400 → repair</li>
          <li>Over 10 years old AND repair over $500 → consider replacing</li>
          <li>Compressor failure on 8+ year unit → strongly consider replacing</li>
          <li>Sealed-system repair on 12+ year unit → almost always replace</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

